@sivabudh global_delay_factor is not a timeout; it controls the delay for various operations. Most of the time you shouldn't need to set this, but some devices are really slow (particularly virtual devices) so you need to tell Netmiko to add more delay into its operations.

You can also generally override specific commands and increase the delay for just that command (if you have a long running command).

You can run the SSH connections concurrently using threads or multiprocesses (as per the above examples). So you can fire off 10 SSH sessions and the operation will complete in a similar time as one SSH connection would have completed.

