@brianjmurrell no, you don't. You can use 127.0.0.1 (or anything else) as in your example. As long as the address you specify in sshuttle is the same to where you forward it should work even if that DNS server does not exist.

```
zone "example.com" IN {
	type forward;
	forwarders { 127.0.0.1; };
};
```
and run sshuttle with
```
$ sshuttle -r user@server --ns-hosts=127.0.0.1
```

